<DOC><DOCNO> AP890325-0109 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 1752EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-25 0491</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0505</SECOND><HEAD>Wet Weather West Of Rockies, Snow In Maine</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A moist Pacific weather system spread showers across most of thewestern third of the nation Saturday, and locally heavy snow fellovernight in Maine.   Most of California had rain Saturday and rain also fell overmuch of the Pacific Northwest and sections of the Intermountainregion between the Sierra Nevada and the Rockies.   The heaviest rain fell in northern California, but southernCalifornia also was hit and most of the Los Angeles area received asteady light rain during the morning, with amounts generally arounda quarter of an inch.   In California's Sierra Nevada range, over 3 inches of rain fellduring the 24 hours ending at 7 a.m. EST at Blue Canyon and at LaPorte, which got 3.56 inches.   Precipitation at Blue Canyon changed to snow late in themorning. Some higher elevations in the northern Sierra Nevada gotaround 1 to 2 feet of snow.   Gusty wind developed over parts of the Southwest during the daywith a gust to 49 mph reported at Cedar City, Calif.   In the Northeast, much of Maine had heavy snow overnight,including 11 inches at Lewiston, 8 inches at Augusta, 6 inches atRumford, and 4 inches at Portland.   That snow changed to rain during the morning and most of itended by midday. Afternoon temperatures in the upper 30s and 40sthroughout the state melted much of the snow.   Elsewhere, showers were scattered over eastern sections of theDakotas and western Minnesota. In eastern North Dakota, most of theprecipitation was in the form of snow or sleet.   Showers spread over northern Michigan, with almost a half-inchof precipitation at Pellston.   A flow of air off the Gulf of Mexico brought ashore enoughmoisture to produce widely scattered showers over southern Texas.   Much of the nation had sunshine and mild temperatures and warmair pushed northward across the Plains, producing noon readings of68 at Rapid City, S.D.; 69 at Denver, and 71 at Chadron, Neb.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 29degrees at South Lake Tahoe, Calif., to 88 at Altus Air Force Base,Okla. Saturday's low in the Lower 48 states was 21 degrees atDevils Lake, N.D.   For Sunday, showers were forecast across the West from theRockies to the Pacific Coast. Snow showers were forecast in much ofNevada and the mountains of Arizona. Scattered showers andthunderstorms were forecast from southern and eastern Texas intowestern Louisiana and Arkansas.   Highs in the 40s and 50s were predicted from the PacificNorthwest to the northern Rockies, along the Canadian border fromMontana to Michigan, and over most of New York state and NewEngland; in the 80s from Texas across the central Gulf Coast statesto South Carolina, Georgia and Florida; and in the 60s and 70sacross much of the rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>